metadata.name: Lines and Planes #85
metadata.description:
A series of lines and planes intersect at random angles in varying densities and color schemes to create an ever changing composition. Each iteration is unique. Rarity features work as follows :
1. Black backgrounds are common, white - less common and red - very rare.
2. Density of lines and planes are less common with increase in density.
3. Angle distribution are almost uniformly distributed.

metadata.name: Three dead trees on earth #253
metadata.description:
"Three dead trees on earth" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel.
This cycle is totally linked to my activity as a scientific researcher. Trees are data structures very much used in computer science and I worked on the random generation of these structures. It seemed interesting to me to make a link between the digital world (and these trees) and nature in danger. The 3 dead trees refer to the old beliefs of the south of France, while questioning us on the mutations of the world, and the risk to neglect our planet. Are the trees of the computer science the dead trees of our forests? To complete my work, I added a red sun, which is in fact a zonotopal subdivision (a complex mathematical object), that is to say a kind of tiling with rhombuses. I wanted to give a Japanese touch to my work, I love the minimalist poetry of Japanese gardens where everything is in its place and in harmony. Here, a desire to pay tribute to the work of Hiroshige.

metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #37
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.name: Unknown Monuments #169
metadata.description:
That Monument belongs to someone.

.Four seasons of the year.
.Three Forest Densities.
.Nine monuments.
.Can be actived or inactive.
.Rare raining.

-

Monuments often seem peaceful,
Perhaps they bring mute regrets,
Maybe bloody words and gestures,
Perhaps even peace itself!

They are always rich and full of glory.
They always cry out to the history of a people

One of these days I'll build a monument.
Not a monument for what's great.
But a monumento for the misunderstood.
A monument of clay and blood.
A monument of old newspaper pieces,
A monument of bones and gold,
A monument covered in autumn leaves,
A damp monument,

Because it brings tears.

-

by Gen Doodler | twitter.com/GenDoodler
